description: Borrowed from Old Norse rún, which is from Proto-Germanic *rūnō (“letter, literature, secret”), which is borrowed either from Proto-Celtic *rūnā or from the same source as it; compare Dutch rune, German Rune and Swedish runa. Compare roun.

entries.meaning: A letter, or character, used in the written language of various ancient Germanic peoples, especially the Scandinavians and the Anglo-Saxons.
A Finnish or Scandinavian epic poem, or a division of one, especially a division of the Kalevala.
A letter or mark used as a mystical or magic symbol.
A verse or song, especially one with mystical or mysterious overtones; a spell or an incantation.
examples: the fiddle sang and sang as ceaselessly as the chanting cicada without, and the frogs intoning their sylvan runes by the waterside.

entries.meaning: (obsolete) Alternative form of roun (“secret or mystery”).
(programming, in the Go programming language) A Unicode code point.
